# Render Logs Access

When debugging production issues, you can query Render logs directly instead of asking the user to check them.

**Investigation default:** For “did X hit production?” or “find this error”, follow **`debug-render-logs-no-false-negatives.mdc`**: **`minutes=120`** + **`limit=500`**, save to file, Node-parse `message`. If the user **just** triggered the event, **poll up to 3 times** with **~60s** between attempts — Render does not document an exact log delay; async delivery and log pipelines mean the first fetch can be empty.

## Endpoint

```
GET https://pb-webhook-server.onrender.com/debug-render-logs
Authorization: Bearer Diamond9753!!@@pb
```

## Query Parameters

| Parameter | Type | Default | Description |
|-----------|------|---------|-------------|
| `minutes` | number | 30 | Fetch logs from last N minutes |
| `startTime` | ISO string | - | Specific start time (UTC) |
| `endTime` | ISO string | - | Specific end time (UTC) |
| `limit` | number | 200 | Max number of log entries (often `hasMore: true` — not full history) |
| `search` | string | - | Server-side filter (unreliable — prefer fetch + parse; see `searching-render-logs.mdc`) |

## Example Queries

**IMPORTANT**:
- On Windows, use `curl.exe` (not PowerShell's `Invoke-WebRequest` which times out).
- One response is a **limited batch** — see `debug-render-logs-no-false-negatives.mdc`. Do not conclude “not in logs” from a single small fetch.
- **Reliable filter**: save JSON to a file, parse with Node, search `message` fields — see `searching-render-logs.mdc`. Piping huge JSON through `findstr` can **truncate lines** and cause **false negatives**.

```bash
# Recent logs (last 5 minutes) — inspect or parse file
curl.exe -s -H "Authorization: Bearer Diamond9753!!@@pb" "https://pb-webhook-server.onrender.com/debug-render-logs?minutes=5&limit=50" -o temp-render-logs.json

# Wider window + high limit when hunting a specific event
curl.exe -s -H "Authorization: Bearer Diamond9753!!@@pb" "https://pb-webhook-server.onrender.com/debug-render-logs?minutes=120&limit=500" -o temp-render-logs.json

# Specific time window (UTC) — Render dashboard may show local time; convert to UTC
curl.exe -s -H "Authorization: Bearer Diamond9753!!@@pb" "https://pb-webhook-server.onrender.com/debug-render-logs?startTime=2026-02-10T10:24:00Z&endTime=2026-02-10T10:30:00Z&limit=200" -o temp-render-logs.json
```

Then filter with the Node snippet in `searching-render-logs.mdc` (not `findstr` on the pipe).

## When to Use

- User reports something isn't working
- Need to investigate webhook failures
- Checking if a feature is being triggered
- Debugging errors in production

**Do not ask the user to check Render logs manually** - query them yourself using this endpoint.
